<TEXT>
more than 700 boeing jetliners operated by 
every major us airline must undergo a comprehensive inspection for 
crosswiring and crossplumbing in their safety systems after 
problems were discovered in 17 aircraft 
the federal aviation administraton in issuing the 
airworthiness directive late tuesday also noted that boeing is 
studying its design production procedures and testing of airliner 
emergency systems to see if changes are needed 
the newly ordered tests are not expected to disrupt airline 
schedules and can be completed anytime over the next 3 weeks while 
the airliners are undergoing routine maintenance 
the order affects 741 newer jetliners flown by us carriers it 
applies to all boeing 737s 747s 757s and 767s built after dec 31 
1980 most foreign airliners using the planes also are expected to 
comply although the faa has no jurisdiction over them 
the comprehensive directive will require functional testing 
of the engine and cargo compartment fire detection warning and 
extinguishing systems both electrical and plumbing to insure that 
crossed wiring or plumbing does not exist said the faa 
announcement 
no accident or emergency has resulted from faulty wiring or 
plumbing found in airliners in recent weeks after the faa issued 
limited directives applying to only specific systems in certain 
types of aircraft 
but the foulups including crosswiring crossplumbing 
incomplete wiring and other problems could have caused shutdown of 
the wrong engine in the event of fire activation of the wrong 
sprinkling system in a cargo hold or lack of any response in 
emergency systems 
the concern arose with speculation that the pilot in a jan 8 
british midland airways 737 crash that killed 44 people in england 
may have been deceived by faulty wiring into shutting down his only 
good engine cause of the crash is still under investigation 
the crash led to similar inspection orders in great britain 
airbus 320s also were included in the british order although 
problems have been found only in boeing aircraft 
jack gamble boeing spokesman said tuesday night that the 
directive is based on service bulletins boeing has been putting out 
in recent months and years service bulletins are sent out each time 
a problem of some sort is found with a model of a plane to all 
carriers using that model and to the faa checks of planes are 
voluntary after a service bulletin is issued 
but if the faa sees a pattern in the bulletins it is likely to 
issue a directive making checks of the airliners mandatory 
its a preventive and precautionary check he said 
faa spokesman fred farrar said the latest order which gives 
airlines 25 days to comply would not disrupt regularly scheduled 
flights he said planes whose systems were already tested under 
previous orders need not retest under the new order 
boeings gamble said a lot of the 57 and 37 stuff already has 
been done 
the faa estimated the inspections would cost airlines a total of 
222000 airline analysts say however that actual cost of 
faaordered inspections is generally two or three times higher than 
the faa estimates 
it said the order is a precautionary measure triggered by 
newly discovered problems with three 757s and a 737 farrar said he 
did not know which airlines reported the latest cases of faulty 
wiring 
on one plane an overheat indicator would have shown a problem in 
the wrong engine in two others fire extinguishers would have been 
triggered in the wrong engines in the fourth an incomplete circuit 
would have prevented a fire extinguisher from firing 
the first crosswiring directive applying only to two 737 models 
found no problems a second triggered by reports of crosswiring in 
two 757s resulted in discovery of five more miswired aircraft 
earlier directives followed discovery of improperly installed 
plumbing in two 767s the inspections exposed four other aircraft 
with similar problems that in the event of a fire in one of two 
holds would have routed extinguishing fluids to the hold that was 
not burning 
the inspections would cover 472 boeing 737s 33 jumbo 747s 123 
757s and 113 767s the faa said 
</TEXT>
