<TEXT>
a food and drug administration panel has set 
new guidelines on how often people need dental xrays saying its 
goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure 
children with healthy teeth may need dental xrays no more than 
once every year or two and dentally healthy adults once every two 
or three years the panel said 
the guidelines reported in the current issue of the journal of 
the american dental association were prompted by concern among some 
experts about the frequency of dental xrays both overuse and 
underuse 
although the radiation risk from a dental xray is extremely 
low our goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure fda 
commissioner frank e young said in statement tuesday 
until these guidelines were developed there were few concrete 
criteria a dentist could use in deciding when xrays were needed 
he said 
young also stressed the flexibility of the guidelines saying 
these are not hard and fast rules in deciding whether an xray is 
needed the dentist must use clinical judgment in evaluating the 
patients needs 
</TEXT>
