<TEXT>
president ranasinghe premadasa who 
completes a turbulent first month in office today is trying hard to 
vanquish a legacy of ethnic violence and chart a more peaceful 
course for his island nation 
since taking over jan 2 he has freed more than 1400 political 
prisoners and lifted tough emergency laws that were imposed 5 years 
ago in an effort to control an insurgency by minority tamil 
extremists 
political rivals credit premadasa with shrewd moves he had to 
do something startling with the looming general elections 
scheduled for feb 15 said kumar ponnabalam leader of the 
opposition all ceylon tamil congress 
despite premadasas efforts an extremist group whose members are 
of the sinhalese ethnic majority has stepped up attacks aimed at 
thwarting the vote 
police say the peoples liberation front killed 600 people in 
january alone a western diplomat speaking on condition of 
anonymity termed the figure a bit farfetched but declined to 
say how many people he thought had been killed 
for premadasa who served as prime minister under former 
president junius r jayewardene the parliamentary elections will be 
vital since his plans could be stalled if his united national party 
does not gain a parliamentary majority 
the period to come is premadasas greatest challenge said 
ralph bultjens a veteran sri lankawatcher and a political science 
professor at the new school in new york feb 15 is his most 
urgent hour 
in the year leading up to the dec 19 presidential election 
sinhalese extremists killed more than 800 people mostly government 
officials supporters and police authorities said 
most of the victims were sinhalese who comprise 75 percent of 
the indian ocean islands 16 million people and dominate the 
government which the front says has made too many concessions to 
the tamils 
during his election campaign premadasa took pains not to blame 
the sinhalese guerrillas for the violence instead he made fervent 
appeals to the front to lay down arms and join mainstream politics 
but premadasas gamble failed said another western diplomat 
who spoke on condition of anonymity the sinhalese extremists are 
bent upon violence and will not heed appeals 
despite the violence premadasa will fulfill campaign promises to 
help the poor said ranjan wijeratna chairman of the united 
national party 
premadasa plans to give 75 monthly to 14 million families that 
live in extreme poverty the annual per capita income of nearly half 
the countrys population is well below the national average of 360 
some of premadasa campaign promises that have already 
materialized 3500 indian soldiers were withdrawn and india agreed 
to consider premadasas promise to change the indiansri lankan 
peace accord into a friendship treaty 
the july 1987 accord an attempt to end the tamil insurgency 
allowed indian troops onto the island to disarm tamil guerrillas 
but indias attempt to play peacemaker for its southern neighbor 
met with resistance from tamil militants and at least 600 indian 
soldiers have been killed about 44000 indian soldiers remain in 
the country 
the tamil separatist war has claimed about 8500 lives most of 
them sinhalese civilians 
