<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency proposed 
today the banning of a pesticide which regulates apple growth and 
increases shelf life because of a link to cancer 
the epa however stopped short of ordering the chemical which 
is marketed under the trade name alar immediately off the market 
because it said it does not consider the health risk severe enough 
for such action 
apple growers during recent years have sharply curtailed use of 
the pesticide also known as daminozide because of government 
concerns that it may cause cancer but according to epa and industry 
estimates about 5 percent of the countrys annual 
200millionbushel apple crop continues to be sprayed with the 
chemical 
the epa in action aimed at eventually banning the chemical said 
it will begin the formal rulemaking for such a ban within 90 days 
and anticipates issuing a final regulation taking alar off the 
market within 18 months officials acknowledged however that the 
process could take much longer if it is contested 
john moore acting epa administrator told reporters there is 
an inescapable and direct correlation between exposure to alar 
and the development of lifethreatening cancerous tumors in test 
mice 
moore said laboratory tests are not expected to be completed for 
another year but that preliminary results although at times 
conflicting showed test animals having cancerous tumors when 
exposed to alar 
the epa estimated the chances of an adult getting cancer as a 
result of alar exposure from eating apples and apple products as 5 
in 100000 but it said the lifetime risk is higher for young 
children because of their greater use of apple products 
moore acknowledged that the agency could seek an emergency 
suspension that would order alar off the market within months but 
he said the agency rejected such an action because of the continuing 
conflicting test data the fact that the tests have not been 
completed and because of the level of risk 
he said that during the 18 months until a final ban is expected 
the risk of an adult getting cancer as a result of alar exposure is 
at most 1 in a million and the risk for a child 9 in 1 million 
we dont think that the added burden of risk over the next 18 
months is of sufficient magnitude to warrant this kind of 
emergency action moore told a news conference 
derl derr president of the international apple institute which 
represents 90 percent of the countrys apple growers said that the 
growers have significantly reduced the use of alar since 1986 
when the epa first seriously considered banning the chemical he 
said no more than 5 percent of the apples grown have the chemical 
which penetrates fruit sprayed on them 
</TEXT>
