<TEXT>
a sudanese rebel leader met with state 
department officials recently as part of a us effort to end 
sudans civil war that has left millions in danger of starvation 
officials said wednesday 
mansour khalid who serves as the foreign envoy of the sudanese 
peoples liberation army arrived in washington last week and asked 
to meet with representatives of president bushs new administration 
state department spokesman charles redman said 
khalid spoke on the telephone with officials of the national 
security council said white house officials who spoke on condition 
of anonymity he also met with julia taft who heads the us 
governments foreign disaster assistance program and has been 
pressing both sides to allow relief convoys safe passage from kenya 
into famine areas said a state department official also speaking 
only on condition he not be named 
redman said that khalid has been here before and that his 
meetings did not reflect a change in us policy khalid has said he 
knows bush from the days both represented their governments at the 
united nations in 1971 and 1972 
until recently the us government had carefully avoided taking 
sides in sudan angering congressional critics who charged that the 
state department was allowing foreign policy considerations to 
overrule humanitarian needs congressional delegations to sudan in 
recent weeks have been told that as many as 500000 sudanese died 
last year of hunger 
in recent months us officials have been taking a slightly more 
critical approach toward the sudanese government of sadiq mahdi 
after he refused to support a tentative ceasefire pact signed by 
one party in his coalition government mahdi has been pressured by 
moslem fundamentalists in his government to reject any pact with the 
predominantly christian and animist rebels 
the united states has been urging the ethiopianbacked spla and 
the government of mahdi to negotiate an end to their fiveyear war 
and to allow foreign relief supplies to reach starving sudanese in 
the southern part of the country 
the sudanese government has supported past us discussions with 
the rebel group and was informed of the meetings with khalid said 
one us official he said the two sides in sudan are also talking 
with each other 
in an effort to bring pressure on mahdi us diplomats in 
ethiopia have been talking more frequently to spla representatives 
and the united states has also been urging the soviet union to get 
involved in efforts to end the war 
the united states enjoyed military basing rights and close ties 
with the sudanese government of gaafar nimeiri but relations with 
sudan deteriorated after he was deposed in a 1985 coup 
</TEXT>
