<TEXT>
state department officials on wednesday 
defended the agencys restrictions on blind persons who apply to 
become diplomats but the officials who spoke at a congressional 
hearing were treated derisively by an audience overwhelmingly 
composed of sightless persons 
under state department policy the blind may apply to become 
foreign service officers but in a policy change that became 
effective late last year they cannot use braille or receive help 
from readers when taking entrance examinations 
more than 100 blind persons crowded into the hearing of the house 
human resources civil service subcommittee and made clear through 
occasional snickers and groans their displeasure with two state 
department witnesses sent to explain the agencys position 
much of the hearing focussed on the case of avraham rabby who 
has been trying unsuccessfully since 1985 to become a career 
diplomat and who testified that the state departments treatment of 
him reflects either sheer ignorance or deliberate deception 
rabby who lives in new york city and has passed five state 
department entrance examinations is a graduate of oxford university 
in england with degrees in spanish and french and has a masters 
degree in business administration from the university of chicago 
he lived for 15 years in england and speaks in the cultured tones 
of a man accustomed to intellectual pursuits he has his own 
consulting business helping disabled people find employment 
rabby 46 rejected the suggestion that gestures such as winks 
and nods form part of the overall message a diplomat must assimilate 
and that therefore the profession is not suitable for a blind person 
no international treaty has ever been decided on the basis of a 
wink or a nod he said 
subcommittee chairman gerry sikorski dminn criticized the 
state department policy and the agencys decision to impose strict 
limits on the degree to which the two department witnesses could 
respond to questions 
the witnesses were charles stout a director in the state 
department personnel office and sheldon yuspeh coordinator of the 
handicapped employment program 
stout said it is difficult for the foreign service to accommodate 
blind persons because of the problem they have in working 
independently from official documents and the requirement that all 
career diplomats be available to serve worldwide on short notice 
including countries which have unfamiliar settings and cultures 
sikorskis position is that federal law requires all government 
and governmentassisted agencies to conduct employment practices 
without discrimination on the basis of handicap 
evan j kemp jr commissioner of the equal employment 
opportunity commission said congress should consider withholding 
state department appropriations if the agency does not demonstrate a 
more flexible attitude toward blind applicants 
