<TEXT>
by the time he was 25 gary martin was an 
american success story a poor black kid from alabama who earned 
degrees from harvard college and columbia law school clerked for a 
federal judge and landed a job with a big miami law firm 
at 28 he was a story of another kind a homeless ivy leaguer 
wandering the streets of new york dressed in rags fishing through 
trash cans finally friends and former classmates hunted him down 
and convinced him to enter a counseling facility 
three years later gary martins story lacks a neat ending at 
31 he is neither back on the fast track nor back on the street 
after living for several years in an apartment provided by the 
bridge inc a mental health rehabilitation agency martin moved 
back to his mothers home in phenix city ala 
he spent two months working as a parttime law clerk but says he 
has no immediate plans to try to resume his career 
in a telephone interview martin said he was pretty much just 
trying to get used to being around here again 
getting to see home again is nice he said its quiet down 
here new york can be kind of a wild place 
it was a wild place for martin who arrived in spring 1985 soon 
after that his money ran out but exactly what drove him onto the 
street remains unclear although he appears to have been depressed 
he has described the period as a sort of urban camping experience 
martins problems seem to have begun in miami where he lost his 
42000ayear job after twice flunking the florida bar exam he 
moved in with some relatives in wilmington del and began a job 
search when things didnt work out martin headed to new york where 
he had attended law school 
after friends who had spotted him on the street obtained a court 
order for his apprehension martin agreed to accept room and 
counseling from the bridge 
for a month the homeless lawyer was news homeless advocates 
said his case showed the breadth of the problem people who learned 
of his plight offered money or jobs although martin clearly was in 
no condition to take advantage of the latter 
since returning to phenix city his only job has been a brief 
stint in the office of attorney michael bellamy bellamy identified 
with martin when he read about him in the newspaper three years ago 
he too had flunked the bar exam the first time he took it 
martin he said did an excellent job i gave him a brief 
to do and it was apparent he was real smart 
but bellamy said he could not afford to keep a clerk martin 
himself said the work there was not the best use for my type of 
law background 
he said he might take the bar exam again and try to get a job 
with a small law firm or a public interest organization preferably 
in atlanta or another large city 
martin still doesnt readily admit to having had a psychological 
problem asked about his time on the street he calls it an odd 
situation i was just trying to deal with a tough situation 
ive always been kind of a selfsufficient person 
george mcdonald a homeless advocate who helped link martin up 
with the bridge said martin always felt above everything there 
in phenix city he has rebuffed suggestions that he seek counseling 
mcdonald says this is not remarkable many homeless people must 
struggle to regain their equilibrium 
but in another respect he said martin is unusual he got 
help 
