<TEXT>
for jose and juanita pichardo cuban 
immigrants in their mid60s owning a tiny beachfront room for their 
golden years was the payback for 30 years of hard work and modest 
living in new york city 
hedy werner wanted a retirement free of mortgage payments and 
troubles when she paid nearly 30000 cash for a room on the 12th 
floor of the carillon hotel now she says her money went to 
gangsters 
the dreams of nearly 300 people who say they thought they were 
buying security in the form of rooms at the oncegrand hotel soured 
almost as fast as developer isaac gamel sold 72year subleases on 
rooms in 1983 
rooms were bought for as little as 20000 as an investment 
believed to be secure through 2055 
five years later the 17story 600room hotel on miami beach is 
mired in lawsuits bankruptcies and foreclosures back under control 
of its original property holder main realty and the tenants face 
eviction 
main realty slipped eviction notices under tenants doors in 
november setting a jan 2 deadline tenants on dec 20 sued all the 
principals in the carillon in late december the landlord agreed not 
to take any action until the case is heard in court expected 
sometime late this year 
despite the reprieve many tenants are worried and confused and 
feel deceived many of the elderly residents could lose their 
investments and because they are living on fixed incomes fear 
for their future 
to live here was to live on top of the world pichardo 67 
said wistfully as he walked across the hotels virtually empty pool 
