<TEXT>
the treasury department announced wednesday it 
plans to borrow 2875 billion next week to replenish the 
governments coffers in a giant debt auction which will feature a 
sale of 30year bonds for the first time since last may 
every three months the government holds three debt sales to 
finance the 27 trillion national debt the auction known as a 
quarterly refunding features the sale of threeyear notes 10year 
notes and 30year bonds 
the government however was prevented from offering any 30year 
bonds at the last two quarterly auctions because of a failure by 
congress to raise the ceiling on issuance of longterm debt 
congress finally passed new legislation before it adjourned late 
last year and william bremner treasury deputy assistant secretary 
for finance said the 30year bonds would be a part of next weeks 
auction 
at a briefing for reporters bremner said treasury still expected 
to have enough total borrowing authority to finance the national 
debt at least until next summer 
many in congress expect the government to bump up against the 
current 28 trillion debt limit sometime in august but bremner 
refused to be specific about the month 
all things being equal we expect to make it through without 
difficulty until the summer he said 
the battle over increasing the debt limit is expected by many in 
congress to be a major showdown with the new administration over 
budget priorities since without legislation to boost the borrowing 
authority the government would face the prospect of missing such 
necessary payments as the monthly social security benefits 
the auctions for next week call for 
975 billion in threeyear notes in minimum denominations of 
5000 to be auctioned tuesday 
95 billion in 10year notes in minimum denominations of 1000 
to be auctioned on wednesday 
95 billion in 30year bonds in minimum denominations of 1000 
to be auctioned on thursday 
</TEXT>
