<TEXT>
legislation to abolish federal fueleconomy 
standards was introduced wednesday by rep bob carr dmich who 
argued that the rules cause the economy to suffer in michigan and 
the nation 
carrs bill which he first introduced last year would end the 
corporate average fueleconomy regulations that require automakers 
to attain a certain minimum gasoline mileage on average throughout 
their fleets of passenger cars 
cafe is a government regulation that is simply not needed 
said carr the time has come to put it aside without such a 
change the two largest domestic automakers face the unfortunate 
prospect of having to limit or stop selling some of the most popular 
cars in america today 
the fueleconomy standard for 1989 models is 265 miles per 
gallon a slightly more stringent level than the 26 mpg standard in 
effect from 1986 through 1988 but below the 275 mpg set as a goal 
by fuelconservation legislation 
the national highway traffic safety administration is considering 
what standard to set for 1990 models president bushs new 
transportation secretary samuel skinner told a senate committee 
this week he would review any mileage standard set by nhtsa 
carrs bill died last year without action by the house energy and 
commerce committee whose chairman rep john dingell also a 
michigan democrat has said the fueleconomy standards appeared to 
be working fairly well 
dingell has yet to take a position on the new legislation carr 
introduced wednesday the committee staff said 
its an educational process said jeff eller a carr aide 
when asked about prospects for the bill this year we now have a 
base of members who understand why cafe should be abolished 
general motors corp and ford motor co have argued for an end to 
the fueleconomy standards saying it forces them to produce smaller 
cars the buying public doesnt want in order to bring their fleets 
within the mileage requirements 
the result they have said is layoffs at largecar assembly 
plants and a lessened ability of us automakers to compete with 
smallbody imports 
chrysler corp with a higher proportion of smaller vehicles in 
its lineup has said it can meet the 275 mpg standard envisioned by 
the law 
