occidental petroleum corp agreed wednesday to 
pay the government 205 million including interest to settle 
allegations that a subsidiary violated federal oil and gas price 
control rules in the late 1970s 
the company also reported its financial results which showed that 
a 45 million provision for the settlement deeply eroded 
fourthquarter income 
but for all of last year occidentals profit rose 26 percent 
despite the cost of the settlement and of lost production caused by 
the explosion of an occidental oil and gas platform in the north sea 
that killed 167 
fourthquarter profit declined to 7 million or 2 cents a share 
from 38 million or 17 cents a share a year earlier largely 
because of the provision for the settlement sales in the quarter 
were 53 billion up from 44 billion in the fourth quarter of 
1987 
occidental said it earned 302 million or 121 a share in 
1988 up from 240 million or 106 a share the previous year 
sales for the year were 194 billion up from 171 billion in 1987 
as to the settlement the department of energy originally sought 
700 million from oxy usa inc oxy usa is the former cities service 
which occidental bought in 1982 after the alleged violations 
occurred 
in settling the administrative case against it occidental didnt 
admit violating department regulations the allegations involve 
actions taken from october 1979 through january 1981 and were 
brought under federal price controls on oil and gas imposed after 
the arab oil embargo 
the energy department press office didnt immediately respond to 
questions about the settlement 
the company agreed to pay 150 million plus 10 percent interest 
over the course of eight years bringing the total to 205 million 
a first payment of 40 million will be made when the settlement 
agreement becomes final a process that involves publishing the 
terms in the federal register and a 30day period for comment by 
interested parties 
the balance of the settlement is to be paid with 1002 percent 
interest in eight annual payments of 206 million 
occidentals financial results like those at other big oil 
companies were boosted by strong gains on petrochemicals even 
though oil and gas prices were depressed 
the company which bought cain chemical co of texas last year 
recorded chemical sales of 14 billion in 1988 up from 780 
million the year before sales at the ibp inc meatprocessing 
subsidiary rose to 24 billion from 2 billion and natural gas 
transmission revenue rose to 733 million from 588 million 
oil and gas sales declined to 701 million from 917 million 
the company didnt reveal the exact cost of lost production from 
the july 6 explosion that destroyed occidentals piper alpha 
platform in the north sea off aberdeen scotland occidental 
executives previously said it would cut yearend profit by between 
13 million and 26 million 
